commentBody:
@Steven M.  
I'm twice 35, but both I and my grandchildren like the movie  It was a gimme for me. 
PS: Deb, I'm sorry for your loss. May you remember him fondly as you solve puzzles.

@Steven M. 

Edna Mode is a legendary character and I’m certain that she has made several well deserved appearances in the NYT crossword in the past year or two. Just a great character and great name, loved by all ages, even us people over 40 who saw the movie when it came out 20 YEARS AGO?!? Did you know that she was voiced by the creator/director of The Incredibles, Brad Bird? 

Ps, thanks to Deb for sharing her lovely, personal story in the column today.

@Wayne Harrison 

I got past that okay, but have no idea why PRE 'weirdly follows T.S.A.'

What no doubt completely obvious little clue detail am I missing?

@Cathy Thanks!  I haven't flown much lately so I figured it had something to do with pre-boarding.  Or maybe it had something to do with a Russian T.S.A.R with a phonetic spelling of 'R', or maybe it had to do with following in the sense of social media followers, but who follows the TSA?

I went back and forth on STEADY/STEELY for some time because I never considered AOL a 'tech' company (just a second rate ISP), and wondered if they were looking for the first name of a 'giant in tech' engineering like TOM Edison, or etc...

Add to that the YouTube prompt just says "Skip" and that whole corner was a troublesome area.

@Jay 

Ha! Spot on!
You have me ROFL😂

@Wark 

Another thoughtful and resonant post from you, thank you! 

"Embrace that which binds us together" is lovely inspiration in these tenuous times.

@Linda Jo 

You got it first yesterday too.  

A mis-spent youth (and adulthood too boot) helped me with this one.

@Janine 
I thought "steady" as well, but put off entering it, and sure enough....

97!!!  That's impressive longevity!  Our Granny was fading when she learned I was pregnant wiith our first child; she rallied and lived long enough to learn that our daughter was born and survived heart surgery at age 5 days....  Then she could rest.

@Lewis I second your bid for more!!!! I really really loved this one :)

"The smallest bit" of WHIT was downright charming lol. 

I do wish this original had stayed: SKIP AD, [Label on a spot remover?].

@Andy 
Thank you. I think of brouhaha as a bit of a fuss, not really a mob - not familiar with the terms 'mob scene' and 'press kit'.
I'm only familiar with a few Greek letters, like the first 4!

@Scott 

"Weird flex, but OK" was, curiously enough, first directed at a tweet by Nobel Peace Prize laureate Malala Yousafzai.
So if anyone ever says it to you, you're in good company.

@Hardroch 
Ngram viewer is kinda interesting here, BRAH vs. BRUH. Looks like the latter is perhaps a slightly more recent term. See:

<a href="https://tinyurl.com/5n7757sa" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/5n7757sa</a>

@Tyler Dickinson 

Really?  Is it common in Belgium?  The rest of Europe?

Because I tend to think of it as a quintessential Americanism.

@Francis 

I had BRaH until I realized that PUCKS was much more likely than packs. You are so right about needing the flexibility to swap things when it's clearly not working. Once I got over my insistence that my answers had to be right I certainly turned into a better solver. 

I had never heard of the ski either, so that was my toughest area, especially cuz I couldn't understand what kind of PAD they wanted at 42 D. Oh, SKIP AD, not S?I PAD.

@Francis 

❤️

I often think about what it would have been like to know him as an adult.... How it would have affected other family relationships and dynamics.
